| RFID Guardian Protects Your Privacy                                |
|   from the don't-look-at-me dept.                                  |
|   posted by CowboyNeal on Thursday May 03, @20:18 (Privacy)        |
|   http://yro.slashdot.org/article.pl?sid=07/05/03/2333244          |
+--------------------------------------------------------------------+

An anonymous reader writes "A new device devised by Amsterdam graduate
student Melanie Rieback is designed to serve as a [0]portable firewall
for RFID tags. The portable battery-powered RFID Guardian uses an access
control list to filter RFID queries, blocking queries that aren't
approved. Rieback, who is also known for being the first researcher to
develop a proof of concept RFID virus, hopes to offer version 3.0 of the
RFID Guardian to the public at cost."

Discuss this story at:
    http://yro.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=07/05/03/2333244

Links:
    0. http://arstechnica.com/articles/culture/rfid-guardian.ars/1


+--------------------------------------------------------------------+
| Death of the UMPC?                                                 |
|   from the go-not-gently dept.                                     |
|   posted by CowboyNeal on Thursday May 03, @21:44 (Intel)          |
|   http://hardware.slashdot.org/article.pl?sid=07/05/03/2337233     |
+--------------------------------------------------------------------+

An anonymous reader writes "Remember the UMPC, that little tablet that
Microsoft once called Origami? Well it looks like that [0]Intel has
scrapped the idea of promoting the UMPC, in favor of a much smaller (and
less capable) Mobile Internet Device (MID). The UMPC is now heading for a
market niche, where it may be replacing the tablet PC as a mobile
computer for field technicians. The MID takes on the role of the original
UMPC concept, but it won't run Vista."

Discuss this story at:
    http://hardware.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=07/05/03/2337233

Links:
    0. http://www.tgdaily.com/content/view/31899/113/


